an, and Tibetan sources concerning events and processes in the Central Asian Buddhist world in the late 19th and early 20th centuries. Set in the final days of the Qing empire when Russian and British empires were expanding into Central Asia, this work examines the interplay of religious, economic and political power among peoples who acknowledged the religious authority of Tibet's Dalai Lama. It focuses on diplomatic initiatives involving the 13th Dalai Lama and other Tibetan Buddhist hierarchs during and after his exile in Mongolia and China, as well as his relations with Mongols, and with Buriat, Kalmyk, and other Russian Buddhists. It demonstrates how these factors shaped historical processes in the region, not least the reformulations of both group identity and political consciousness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aBuddhismy19th centuryzAsia, Central. 0aBuddhismy20th centuryzAsia, Central. 0aBuddhismzAsia, CentralxHistoryy19th century. 0aBuddhismzAsia, CentralxHistoryy20th century. 0aDalai lamasxHistoryy19th century. 0aDalai lamasxHistoryy20th century. 4aAsian Studies. 4aAsian history. 4aBuddhism. 4aCentral Asia. 4aEast Asia and North East Asia. 4aEast Asia, Far East. 4aHistory of religion. 4aReligion and Theology. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / General.2bisacsh  aBuddhist modernity, Central Asia, Tibet.1 aDaichi, Wada, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKitinov, Baatr, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuzmin, Sergius L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMakoto, Tachibana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKay, Alex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKay, Alex, eeditor.4edt4http://